description: Maybe torosa?

Found in Jackson Demo. Forest, at the base of a redwood, in a mixed redwood, d. fir forest.

Gills are very dense, and had an intense odor of almonds, with sweet-spicy odors also. Medium sized, about 4 inches in diameter.

Id’ed with Arora’s MD. I’m not sure if this has moved to Gymnopus or Rhodocollybia.
Uploaded from film photos taken on hike in 2003

description:
Love that light!



Birding mini-challenge (view full-size): find the 2nd coot (easy) & the shoveler (harder).  And ID the black specks in the trees.  For the real pros: ID the bird facing the shoveler -- I couldn't tell you what it is, & I was there!  Actually, I have a pretty good guess -- let's see if anybody else says the same thing (or comes up with something better).  I can tell you that it's nothing unusual (if it were, I'd remember it).

With domestic Muscovy Duck

A comparison with domestic greylag stock may be found here -- note the bolder white ring in front of bill, petite size & barring on belly of adult. These appear to be frontalis, going by the light gray-brown plumage; see digitallibrary.amnh.org/dspace/bitstream/handle/2246/2758...

growth habit shot here: www.flickr.com/photos/anitagould/8225480/ San Gabriel Valley (S CA) coastal sage scrub habitat, 2/27/03 Height ~1.5m, flowers ~1 cm long Thank you to urtica & off my front porch for the ID. California endemic. Not something I had seen a lot of.
Here you go, Zen. This is actually the same shot as www.flickr.com/photos/anitagould/7919821/, just cropped tight. Still pretty sharp -- was surprised at how much mag I could get away with.

ID question: Because of the enormous size differential, I originally assumed that the little guys were true GWFs, & the big ones were greylag-derived domestic stock. But if I'm reading my Natl Geo Field Guide correctly, any white on the "front" makes it a GWF, which would make the little ones the tundra subspecies (Anser albifrons albifrons??) and the big ones the taiga ssp (Anser albifrons elgasi). HOWEVER, they really don't exhibit any of the expected plumage darkness/barring differences. That size difference seems utterly excessive too, but I took a ruler to the photo and to the drawings in the field guide, and a very rough (uncorrected for perspective) back-of-the-envelope session suggested that the little guys are almost 90% of the body mass expected for tundra birds relative to taiga. Comments? Click here for a cropped closeup of the GWF's.

This is the same bird as in www.flickr.com/photos/anitagould/4780808/,where the gorget (throat) looks dead black. They are iridescent, & show color only when they catch the light. This little guy was so close and the sun was at just the right angle. Even so, I got very lucky -- snapped probably a dozen shots, trying every time he looked my way & the gorget caught the light, & this is the only one that came out like this. I don't have a "real camera" with a lens appropriate for catching wildlife (this was taken with my Olympus prosumer, which only has a 3X optical zoom; this was before I started digiscoping thru binocs -- not that that works any too reliably), so I'm pretty pleased at getting any shot of a hummer -- especially one taken in the wild instead of at a feeder.
I was lucky enough to see a handful of these wintering in the LA area.  The only place they can commonly be found is wintering in California's Central Valley.

"When life sends you lemons, make lemonade."  I'm actually quite pleased with this particular pitcher of lemonade.  

This bird flew just as I was about to snap its portrait.  Managed to get a shot off, and it actually caught the bird beautifully, but it was at the very edge of the photo.  Tried cropping out just the egret, but a) it didn't really have enough resolution to stand up well to that, & b) the composition was just dead as a doornail.  Then I hit upon the present vertical crop, with echoes of a Japanese scroll, & it really came alive.  

Found that I needed to add the white letterboxing for Flickr, or else the square thumbnail just showed water!

These are an exotic species in the US. They seem to be breeding here, & will probably be considered naturalized at some point. It took me a while to ID them, but they were so striking I knew they had to be something special. Look here for the beautiful colors hidden under those wings. These 2 (probably young ganders -- see very informative post from Robin Dude below) were in S CA in winter, but I have also seen them in NJ.

Not a great shot (I took it so I could ID the thing -- and didn't succeed until I happened to see it here on Flickr!), but we need the species in the WNA pool. Anybody got a better one? Or want to invite that one from the ID thread?

For an entire year I had this listed as "Bloomin' UBO (Unidentified Blooming Object): Mustard (Brassicaceae), Lepidium (peppergrass) species?" Thank you to Naomi_bot for finally ID'ing it. I uploaded a growth habit shot: www.flickr.com/photos/anitagould/8495623/; see comment there from Naomi. Growing in the general vicinity of the nature center; perhaps planted?
Blooming in a natural area in Eaton Canyon. California Bush Sunflower, Encelia californica. Posted a closeup now: www.flickr.com/photos/anitagould/3313337672/
